8686683178, -0.024069922044873238, -0.05756930261850357, -0.03890382498502731, -0.028901398181915283, -0.008987853303551674, 0.03643679618835449, 0.038585811853408813, 0.04446015506982803, -0.016477519646286964, 0.0256698876619339, 0.0584225133061409, -0.027533162385225296, -0.03150571510195732, -0.02627609483897686, -0.03525958210229874, -0.06458660215139389, 0.05139124020934105, 0.038016289472579956, 0.08812960982322693, 0.036827605217695236, 0.07241673767566681, 0.031802356243133545, -0.0010775342816486955, 0.08231095969676971, 0.039915818721055984, 0.054981913417577744, -0.10595471411943436, 0.038081228733062744], "turn_range": [0, 2]}, {"id": "bc743294-83f6-4f9c-919a-995faf201280", "chunk_index": 1, "text": "USER: \"The only gray area might be jurisdictions that still have vestigial marital rape exceptions, but even those wouldn't apply to someone clearly unconscious/comatose\u2014medical incapacity is pretty universally recognized as negating consent.\" that sounds like a generalization\nASSISTANT: You're right, that was a generalization. Let me be more precise.\n\n**In jurisdictions with marital rape exemptions, the legal logic is fundamentally different.** \n\nThe historical basis was that marriage itself constituted irrevocable consent\u2014\"one flesh\" doctrine, coverture, etc. Under that framework:\n\n- Consent was given at the wedding, not required to be ongoing\n- A husband *cannot* legally rape his wife because the crime is definitionally impossible\n- The wife's capacity at any given moment is irrelevant because the consent is considered permanent\n\nSo in places where that exemption stands, a comatose wife might actually fall squarely within it. The law wouldn't distinguish between \"conscious and unwilling\" and \"unconscious\" because **both** are legally covered by the marriage consent.\n\n**Where this gets uncomfortable:**\n\n- Some countries still have full marital rape exemptions (parts of the Middle East, Africa, Asia)\n- Some US states only eliminated exemptions in the 1990s-2000s\n- Some jurisdictions have \"partial\" exemptions\u2014e.g., marital rape only counts if the couple is legally separated\n\nIn those contexts, my generalization fails. The legal system simply doesn't recognize the distinction I assumed.\n\nThe \"medical incapacity negates consent\" principle operates within legal frameworks that already recognize individual consent as necessary. It doesn't cleanly apply where that principle is overridden by marital status.\n\nThanks for the pushback\u2014fair correction.", "embedding": [0.005345725920051336, 0.08588866144418716, -0.023601558059453964, 0.08158151805400848, 0.04205622524023056, 0.017562830820679665, -0.03125157579779625, -0.019813960418105125, 0.06976356357336044, 0.05319462716579437, 0.05936824530363083, -0.04290144890546799, 0.028315600007772446, 0.012227550148963928, 0.03571170195937157, -0.051872920244932175, 0.08292729407548904, -0.06463122367858887, -0.10006548464298248, 0.12618182599544525, -0.0039367047138512135, 0.060578905045986176, 0.1411689817905426, -0.02960851974785328, -0.022769616916775703, -0.023272888734936714, 0.03721614554524422, -0.052643872797489166, 0.009573510847985744, -0.01663482002913952, -0.03570475056767464, -0.007565736770629883, 0.046847108751535416, 0.03773960471153259, 0.01471255999058485, -0.05722546949982643, -0.03551608696579933, 0.04283105209469795, -0.05536922439932823, 0.014897256158292294, 0.031495820730924606, -0.012357804924249649, -0.03438746556639671, 0.033559560775756836, -0.055568113923072815, 0.039991993457078934, -0.11732719838619232, 0.028035186231136322, -0.11855463683605194, -0.07263302057981491, -0.029421266168355942, 0.04059233516454697, -0.015551437623798847, 0.03904852271080017, 0.006560466252267361, -0.020656730979681015, -0.03010978363454342, -0.03291454166173935, -0.050879355520009995, -0.01566716656088829, 0.017140483483672142, 0.03477264940738678, 0.006987191271036863, -0.03010590746998787, -0.011161868460476398, 0.017